{{Infobox Military Conflict |conflict=Siege of Trebizond |image= |caption= |partof=the [[Byzantine-Georgian wars]] |date=April 1282 |place=[[Trabzon|Trebizond]], [[Asia Minor]] |result=Trebizondian victory |combatant1=[[Empire of Trebizond]] |combatant2=[[Kingdom of Georgia]] |commander1=[[John II of Trebizond]] |commander2=David }} The '''Siege of Trebizond''' in April 1282 was an unsuccessful [[siege]] of [[Trabzon|Trebizond]], the capital of the [[Empire of Trebizond|namesake empire]], by the [[Kingdom of Georgia|Georgians]] under a certain David (either [[David VI of Georgia|David I of Imereti]] or a confusion with [[Demetrius II of Georgia]]). Little is known about the attack, but it may have relied on support within the Trebizondian aristocracy, which opposed the rapprochement of Emperor [[John II of Trebizond]] ([[reign]]ed 1280–1297) with the [[Palaiologos|Palaiologan]] [[Byzantine]] court at [[Constantinople]].
